<TEXT>
the sandinista government and 
usbacked rebels are closer than ever to ending their 6year war 
but the last few steps to halt the fighting will be the most 
difficult 
the final measures are particularly crucial for the rebels known 
as contras who may negotiate themselves out of existence in peace 
talks scheduled to resume tuesday 
the rebels do not have the political structure to survive as a 
separate organization on the nicaraguan political scene their role 
likely will be taken over by the political parties already 
established in the country 
despite their rhetoric and posturing the contras and the 
government have been getting closer to a permanent agreement and 
have set a temporary truce that no one wants to break 
the two sides signed a preliminary agreement on march 23 in 
sapoa a small village on the costa rican border 
a 60day ceasefire which expired last tuesday has been 
extended until the two sides renew their discussions in managua the 
nicaraguan capital 
during the last negotiating session the government agreed to 
discuss some political reforms the contra leadership considers 
essential these include calls for political pluralism equality 
before the law the right to strike and a pluralistic electoral 
system 
the reforms deal with definitions of democratization 
concepts that first led to the war which has killed more than 
26000 people and ruined the countrys economy 
the contra leadership feels the sandinista regime is 
undemocratic repressive and based on marxismleninism 
when it comes to definition of freedom of the press civil 
rights human rights democracy we are using the same words with 
different meanings we are talking about two interpretations of 
reality based on different ideologies said virgilio godoy leader 
of the opposition independent liberal party 
i am reasonably optimistic there will be an agreement he 
said it is not a question here of defeating the government at the 
negotiating table but of finding a way to live together 
luis rivas leiva a contra adviser said the government must 
learn to live with what they term petite bourgeoisie we can live 
with some of their leaders 
bayardo arce deputy coordinator of the political commission of 
the ruling sandinista national liberation front said there are 
some in the opposition who have realized that there is political 
room for them here 
arce rejected charges that the government is trying to impose a 
communist state 
we came to power talking about building socialism in 
nicaragua he said but as we developed our struggle we 
understood the national realities and we opted for a system of mixed 
economy with private and government property 
eric ramirez president of the opposition social christian party 
called the sandinistas pragmatic and opportunistic but said 
there was little chance of a definite agreement on democratic 
reforms 
democratization is utopian in a country like ours where there 
has been no democracy for more than 60 years he said what we 
need is a continued process of democratic practices to test the 
political will of the government 
if we do not agree on this he said the government will 
act unilaterally enacting electoral laws and other changes that 
will make it look good abroad while still talking to a divided 
opposition 
the sandinista government already has announced plans for 
municipal elections before the 1990 presidential elections 
opposition party leaders believe the contras as an organization 
served a purpose in forcing the government to the negotiating table 
but are at their weakest while negotiating an end to the war 
ramirez said they will have to return and rejoin one of 
nicaraguas 14 political parties or form another party which is 
the last thing nicaragua needs ramirez said 
