<TEXT>
two pennsylvania women overcame a challenge from the 
soviet union to win the largest global card game ever played the 
world bridge federation announced sunday 
it said jan horwitz and barbara norante of butler pa won the 
bridge contest beating 84356 rivals who played simultaneously in 94 
countries beginning at 8 pm friday and ending saturday morning 
results tabulated saturday were released sunday by the 
federation which organized the event 
their winning score on 24 bridge hands was 7633 percent the 
same hands which took an average of 35 hours to complete were 
played at each location in 2500 cities 
the soviet union competing for the first time held a 
comfortable lead until north america the last to join the 
elaborately timed schedule turned in its results 
names of the soviet players who scored 7592 percent were not 
given 
we got a call with the results from the official bridge league 
in moscow but the line was bad and we were cut off before we got 
the names or where they had played said albert dormer spokesman 
for the bridge federation 
he said the epson worldwide bridge contest will take a place in 
the guinness book of world records as the biggest bridge contest 
ever played beating out a record set last year by the same contest 
in which 73256 people participated 
dormer said the contest also holds the record for the largest 
number of people competing simultaneously in any sport 
by coming in second worldwide the soviet pair will be recognized 
as the european champions 
dormer said that although 50 million people worldwide play 
bridge it had been frowned on in the soviet union as a frivolous 
capitalist game however he said it has gained greater acceptance 
since soviet world chess masters anatoly karpov and garry kasparov 
have been seen playing it between chess rounds 
third place winners were from peru and were identified only as 
garcia and rane they scored 75 percent 
