<TEXT>
several navy rescue swimming instructors 
forced a recruit into a swimming pool shortly before he collapsed 
and died despite his protests that he wanted to quit two 
instructors testified sunday 
petty officer 1st class raymond w jablonowski a safety observer 
at the time of the march 2 death said the instructors more or 
less tossed airman recruit lee mirecki into the pool at pensacola 
naval air station 
they put him back in the water said petty officer 2nd class 
bennie t giles an instructor he wasnt thrown into the water 
he was more or less slid into the water 
the two men testified during a navy investigative hearing here on 
involuntary manslaughter and conspiracy to commit battery charges 
against five instructors and a dereliction of duty count against the 
schools commanding officer lt thomas a torchia 
the hearing scheduled to continue monday is to determine 
whether the six should be courtmartialed 
a doctor testified saturday that mirecki 19 of appleton wis 
died of apparent heart failure most likely induced by fear 
i remember him saying i cant do it i cant do it giles 
said i remember him saying he didnt want to go back in the 
pool 
giles said he could identify only one of the defendants petty 
officer 1st class david j smith as being among a group of 
instructors who forced mirecki back into the pool 
jablonowski said he could remember another defendant in the 
group petty officer 2nd class frankie d deaton 
giles said petty officer 1st class richard e blevins another of 
the defendants took charge of the instruction session when mirecki 
first left the pool jablonowski said blevins was known around the 
school as the antichrist 
neither giles nor jablonowski were charged 
after mirecki was back in the water giles said he talked to him 
and the recruit calmed down but he said that within minutes petty 
officer 2nd class michael combe dived in and put mirecki into a head 
hold the exercise called for recruits to extricate themselves from 
such holds 
earlier testimony indicated that after he was forced back in the 
water mirecki grabbed on to a rope dividing the shallow and deep 
ends of the pool but combe and petty officer 2nd class john zelenock 
pulled him loose combe and zelenock were the other instructors 
charged 
giles and jablonowski both said mirecki apparently escaped from 
the hold by combe just before collapsing 
jablonowski said he signaled to end the exercise when he noticed 
mirecki getting weaker 
combe then brought mirecki to the side of the pool where 
instructors and corpsmen tried to revive him giles said 
giles said there was no formal policy requiring one or more 
instructors to remain out of the water as safety observers but that 
they took turns observing during the drill he said 
under questioning by cmdr daniel j dalesio the investigating 
officer giles said there was no release signal for students to give 
if they were in trouble while in an instructors grasp and that 
there was no formal safety indoctrination as part of the course 
taken to become an instructor 
under questioning by lawyers for the defendants and government 
giles denied that zelenock punched mirecki and said he was unable to 
recall when during the series of events students were told to turn 
away and sing the national anthem 
students had testified they were told to sing when mirecki 
allegedly was being forced screaming back into the pool 
