<TEXT>
california voters who sparked a 
nationwide taxpayer revolt with proposition 13 a decade ago are 
being asked in a series of ballot measures whether they are having 
some second thoughts 
although gloomy predictions of fiscal disaster remain largely 
unrealized since the measure cut property taxes by 7 billion or an 
average of 57 percent proposition 13 has had its visible effects 
the public increasingly pays for services that once were free 
including parks and recreation programs public grounds look 
scruffier than they did 10 years ago as officials have cut back on 
maintenance 
state bailouts and creative funding schemes are credited with 
keeping most local governments afloat since the measure was approved 
june 6 1978 but many agree that schools and rural counties have 
suffered under the cuts 
so on tuesday voters in 26 of the states 57 counties will 
decide whether to raise sales and other taxes in their areas to pay 
for highways schools libraries jails and other services that were 
threatened or eliminated by proposition 13 
at the same time two rival statewide measures proposition 71 
and proposition 72 will ask voters whether to ease a 
constitutional spending limit and provide more money for schools or 
highways 
the spending limit in the form of an initiative written by 
taxcut pioneer paul gann was approved in a special election nine 
months after proposition 13 it requires that spending be strictly 
tied to increases in population and the nationwide cost of living 
the two new measures would alter that limit proposition 71 
whose main supporter is state schools superintendent bill honig 
would permit additional funding for schools proposition 72 written 
by gann himself would allow new money for highway construction 
republican gov george deukmejian grappling with a 11 billion 
budget deficit opposes both measures 
other issues on tuesdays ballot include a proposal to empower 
the state to quarantine aids victims and local measures that could 
close the rancho seco nuclear power plant and divide san bernardino 
county into two 
california also is holding a us senate primary along with new 
mexico montana and new jersey montana in addition is having 
primaries in both parties for governor 
proposition 13 whose war cry was quickly picked up by voters in 
massachusetts and other states decreed that property tax 
assessments be rolled back immediately to 197576 levels it limited 
annual property taxes to 1 percent of the market value and 
stipulated that assessed values and thus taxes could be increased 
by only 2 percent annually until a property is sold then the new 
owners property tax bill starts at 1 percent of the purchase price 
the measure also made it extremely difficult for local school 
districts to raise property taxes requiring that voters approve any 
new taxes by a twothirds margin 
the year before proposition 13 was approved local governments 
received 103 billion in property taxes according to the state 
board of equalization in 197879 the first year after proposition 
13 that figure plunged to 49 billion 
the immediate crunch was eased by the state which contributed 
44 billion in 197879 but over the years that state support has 
worn thin 
mary anne houx president of the california school boards 
association said there is little money for vocational education 
afterschool sports and fine arts programs for the states 45 
million students 
its not like it was before when the board of education could 
raise money locally and for the big bucks we could go to the voters 
and ask for approval with a simple majority said houx 
many school libraries have been closed or forced to curtail their 
hours more than 11 billion is needed for new school construction 
throughout the state and deferred maintenance costs are approaching 
150 million houx said 
the city of oaklands street repair unit faces 60 million in 
deferred maintenance costs that built up in the eight years after 
proposition 13 passed in 1986 residents approved a 15year sales 
tax increase to pay for street maintenance and repair 
an increasing number of residents of humboldt county in the 
northwestern section of the state are driving on gravel as 
officials give up on maintaining many deteriorating roads 
shasta county with 125000 residents replaced a 73bed public 
hospital that also served several neighboring counties with a clinic 
