<DOCNO> AP880605-0088 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
even party tricks can have scientific 
interest and a towson state college chemistry professor will tell a 
conference this week about the tiny sparks that appear when you bite 
wintergreen candy in the dark 
linda sweeting has been researching the phenomenon technically 
known as triboluminescence for five years crushing candies in her 
laboratory and carefully measuring the dim flashes shell present 
her findings at the third chemical congress of north america in 
toronto 
she admits she also sometimes ducks into closets to crunch the 
candy and watch the bluish sparks of mouth lightning 
substances that flash when theyre rubbed crushed or broken 
include sugar salt quartz and human bones 
triboluminescence a name drawn from the greek word tribein 
meaning to rub was first reported by sir francis bacon in 1605 
ms sweeting 46 took advantage of recent technological advances 
in highly accurate measuring instruments to confirm basic theories 
about triboluminescence developed in the 1930s and to add more 
accurate knowledge about the range of light emitted 
she drew upon wintergreen candy studies conducted in the 1930s by 
princeton university researcher e newton harvey 
she said the tiny sparks are created because when sucrose sugar 
crystals fracture under pressure positive and negative electrical 
charges separate voltage builds up until electrons leap across the 
fracture and the discharge makes nitrogen molecules in the air emit 
a tiny burst of light 
that light comes mainly in the invisible ultraviolet region of 
the spectrum but when wintergreen is added the light becomes 
visible as blue sparks because wintergreen molecules glow when 
excited by the flash of the initial spark a tiny reaction that ends 
in milliseconds 
although he has not seen the results to be presented in toronto 
jeffrey zink a professor of chemistry at the university of 
california at los angeles who furthered the research in the early 
1980s said he didnt find the mechanism to be quite as ms sweeting 
described it he said its behavior could vary from crystal to 
crystal 
ms sweeting said she stands by her research which was very 
carefully done on the same batch of crystals 
i guess most of the scientific community would think this is 
not real important she said but its fundamental knowledge of 
crystals how energy flows in and out of molecules and there are 
going to be practical applications down the road 
as an example she suggested that a triboluminescent film could 
could be used to coat parts of orbiting satellites so that 
earthbased instruments could detect any light emissions produced 
when the materials are put under unexpected stress 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

